<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="424" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,804,1207]" box="[151,1436,804,825]" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,804,825]" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">1. Tarsomere 5 of mesothoracic leg normal, without modified setae................................................2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,804,1207]" box="[151,1429,833,854]" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
<keyLead box="[151,1429,833,854]" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
- Tarsomere 5 of mesothoracic leg with modified setae (
<figureCitation box="[746,807,833,854]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6. 1, 2" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[337,1263,812,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[324,1263,808,1884]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. 1, 2. Habropogon appendiculatus. 1. Head, frontal view. 2. Mesotarsomeres of male. 3, 4. H. latifrons. 3. Head, frontal view; 4. Anepisternum, lateral view illustrating dorsal hair patch. 5, 6. H. longiventris. 5. Head, frontal view. 6. Anepisternum, lateral view illustrating dorsal setal row." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847946/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
)..................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schiner" authorityYear="1867" box="[1254,1429,833,854]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Habropogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="appendiculatus">
<emphasis box="[1254,1429,833,854]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">H. appendiculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,804,1207]" box="[151,1436,862,883]" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,862,883]" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">2. Distance between mystax and antennal sockets equal to or less than combined length of scape and pedicel...............3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,804,1207]" box="[151,1436,892,913]" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,892,913]" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">- Distance between mystax and antennal sockets wider than combined length of scape and pedicel.......................4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,804,1207]" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
<keyLead pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
3. Upper margin of mystax triangular, nearly reaching antennal sockets. Anepisternum dorsally with hairs (
<figureCitation box="[1226,1315,921,942]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6. 1, 2" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[337,1263,812,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[324,1263,808,1884]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. 1, 2. Habropogon appendiculatus. 1. Head, frontal view. 2. Mesotarsomeres of male. 3, 4. H. latifrons. 3. Head, frontal view; 4. Anepisternum, lateral view illustrating dorsal hair patch. 5, 6. H. longiventris. 5. Head, frontal view. 6. Anepisternum, lateral view illustrating dorsal setal row." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847946/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">Figs 3, 4</figureCitation>
).................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1871" box="[1319,1429,950,971]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Habropogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latifrons">
<emphasis box="[1319,1429,950,971]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">H. latifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,804,1207]" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
<keyLead pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
- Upper margin of mystax rounded, not reaching antennal sockets. Anepisternum dorsally with macrosetae (
<figureCitation box="[1244,1333,980,1001]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6. 1, 2" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[337,1263,812,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[324,1263,808,1884]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. 1, 2. Habropogon appendiculatus. 1. Head, frontal view. 2. Mesotarsomeres of male. 3, 4. H. latifrons. 3. Head, frontal view; 4. Anepisternum, lateral view illustrating dorsal hair patch. 5, 6. H. longiventris. 5. Head, frontal view. 6. Anepisternum, lateral view illustrating dorsal setal row." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847946/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">Figs 5, 6</figureCitation>
)............................................................................................ 
<taxonomicName authority="Loew" authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1847" box="[1225,1435,1009,1030]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Habropogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longiventris">
<emphasis box="[1225,1375,1009,1030]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">H. longiventris</emphasis>
Loew
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,804,1207]" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
<keyLead pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
4. Leg reddish, hind femur dorsally and usually fore- and mid-femur with dark stripe. Anepisternum anterodorsally and postpronotal lobe with long white hairs. Dorsocentral setae few in number (less than 5), not reaching transverse suture. Hypopygium reddish (
<figureCitation box="[308,404,1097,1118]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1387,1410]" captionTargetBox="[321,1266,267,1358]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[321,1266,267,1366]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 11. Habropogon mesasiaticus. 7. Head, frontal view. 8. Anepisternum, lateral view. 9, 10. Habitus, lateral. (9) and dorsal (10) view. 11. Hypopygium, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847948/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">Figs 7–11</figureCitation>
)........................................................................ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lehr" authorityYear="1960" box="[1273,1430,1097,1118]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Habropogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mesasiaticus">
<emphasis box="[1273,1295,1097,1118]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1307,1430,1097,1118]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">mesasiaticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,804,1207]" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
<keyLead pageId="7" pageNumber="424">
- Leg black, femora and tibiae with reddish spot with indistinct boundary. Anepisternum anterodorsally without hairs, postpronotal lobe with short white hairs. Dorsocentral setae long, distinct, reaching or even crossing transverse suture. Hypopygium black (
<figureCitation box="[289,398,1185,1206]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 12 – 15" captionStart-1="FIGURES 16 – 21" captionStartId-0="5.[151,264,1918,1941]" captionStartId-1="6.[151,264,991,1014]" captionTargetBox-0="[327,1263,800,1887]" captionTargetBox-1="[360,1227,224,955]" captionTargetId-0="figure@5.[327,1266,799,1887]" captionTargetId-1="figure@6.[340,1247,213,961]" captionTargetPageId-0="5" captionTargetPageId-1="6" captionText-0="FIGURES 12 – 15. Habropogon lehri sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 12. Head, frontal view. 13. Anepisternum, lateral view. 14, 15. Habitus, lateral (14) and dorsal (15) views." captionText-1="FIGURES 16 – 21. Line drawings of male genitalia of Habropogon lehri sp. nov., holotype. 16, 17. Hypopygium, lateral (16) and dorsal (17) view. 18 – 20. The same gonocoxite in different views. 21. Aedeagus, lateral view." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/847950/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/847952/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="424">Figs 12–21</figureCitation>
)......................................................................... 
